u20137\n|6th\n|2019\n|-\n|align=left|[[2020 MAAC Men's Basketball Tournament|MAAC]]\n!scope=\"row\" style=\"text-align:left\"|[[2019\u201320 Siena Saints men's basketball team|Siena]] {{efn|name=Siena|Siena received the automatic bid<ref>{{cite news |url=https://maacsports.com/tournaments/?id=1577&path=mbkb |title=2020 MAAC Men's Basketball Championship |accessdate=March 12, 2020}}</ref>after the MAAC Tournament was cancelled due to the [[2020 coronavirus pandemic in the United States|Coronavirus pandemic]].}}\n|20-10\n|7th\n|2010\n|-\n|align=left|[[2020 MAC Men's Basketball Tournament|MAC]]\n!scope=\"row\" style=\"text-align:left\"| [[2019\u201320 Akron Zips men's basketball team|Akron]] {{efn|name=Akron|Akron received the automatic bid<ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=B4HJQ5caDz4&feature=youtu.be |title=MAC Tournament Press Conference: March 12, 2020 |accessdate=March 12, 2020}}</ref> after the MAC Tournament was cancelled due to the [[2020 coronavirus pandemic in the United States|Coronavirus pandemic]].}}\n|24-7\n|5th\n|2013\n|-\n|align=left|[[2020 MEAC Men's Basketball Tournament|MEAC]]\n! colspan=\"4\"| Tournament cancelled, no automatic bid\n|-\n|align=left|[[2020 Missouri Valley Conference Men's Basketball Tournament|Missouri Valley]]\n!scope=\"row\" style=\"text-align:left\"|[[2019\u201320 Bradley Braves men's basketball team|Bradley]]\n|23\u201311\n|10th\n|2019\n|-\n|align=left|[[2020 Mountain West Conference Men's Basketball Tournament|Mountain West]]\n!scope=\"row\" style=\"text-align:left\"|[[2019\u201320 Utah State Aggies men's basketball team|Utah State]]\n|26\u20138\n|22nd\n|2019\n|-\n|align=left|[[2020 Northeast Conference Men's Basketball Tournament|NEC]]\n!scope=\"row\" style=\"text-align:left\"|[[2019-20 Robert Morris Colonials men's basketball team|Robert Morris]]\n|20\u201314\n|9th\n|2015\n|-\n|align=left|[[2020 Ohio Valley Conference Men's Basketball Tournament|Ohio Valley]]\n!scope=\"row\" style=\"text-align:left\"|[[2019\u201320 Belmont Bruins men's basketball team|Belmont]]\n|26\u20137\n|9th\n|2019\n|-\n|align=left|[[2020 Pac-12 Conference Men's Basketball Tournament|Pac-12]]\n! colspan=\"4\"| Tournament cancelled, no automatic bid\n|-\n|align=left|[[2020 Patriot League Men's Basketball Tournament|Patriot League]]\n!scope=\"row\" style=\"text-align:left\"|[[2019\u201320 Boston University Terriers men's basketball team|Boston University]]\n|21\u201313\n|8th\n|2011\n|-\n|align=left|[[2020 SEC Men's Basketball Tournament|SEC]]\n!scope=\"row\" style=\"text-align:left\"|[[2019-20 Kentucky Wildcats men's basketball team|Kentucky]]{{efn|name=Kentucky|Kentucky received the automatic bid after the SEC Tournament was cancelled due to the [[2020 coronavirus pandemic in the United States|Coronavirus pandemic]].<ref>{{cite web |title=SEC cancels remainder of Men's Basketball Tournament |url=https://www.secsports.com/article/28891598/sec-cancels-remainder-men-basketball-tournament |website=SECSports.com}}</ref>}}\t\n|25\u20136\n|60th\n|2019\n|-\n|align=left|[[2020 Southern Conference Men's Basketball Tournament|Southern]]\n!scope=\"row\" style=\"text-align:left\"|[[2019\u201320 East Tennessee State Buccaneers men's basketball team|East Tennessee State]]\n|30\u20134\n|11th\n|2017\n|-\n|align=left|[[2020 Southland Conference Men's Basketball Tournament|Southland]]\n! colspan=\"4\"| Tournament cancelled, no automatic bid\n|-\n|align=left|[[2020 SWAC Men's Basketball Tournament|SWAC]]\n! colspan=\"4\"| Tournament cancelled, no automatic bid\n|-\n|align=left|[[2020 Summit League Men's Basketball Tournament|Summit League]]\n|[[2019-20 North Dakota State Bison men's basketball team|North Dakota State]]\n|25\u20138\n|5th\n|2019\n|-\n|align=left|[[2020 Sun Belt Conference Men's Basketball Tournament|Sun Belt]]\n! colspan=\"4\"| Tournament cancelled, no automatic bid\n|-\n|align=left|[[2020 WAC Men's Basketball Tournament|WAC]]\n!scope=\"row\" style=\"text-align:left\"| [[2019\u201320 New Mexico State Aggies men's basketball team|New Mexico State]] {{efn|name=New Mexico State|New Mexico State received the automatic bid<ref>{{cite news|url=https://twitter.com/WACsports/status/1238132722620493824/photo/1 |title= WAC Official Statement |accessdate=March 12, 2020}}</ref> after the WAC Tournament was cancelled due to the [[2020 coronavirus pandemic in the United States|Coronavirus pandemic]].}}\n|25-6\n|23rd\n|2019\n|-\n|align=left|[[2020 West Coast Conference Men's Basketball Tournament|WCC]]\n!scope=\"row\" style=\"text-align:left\"|[[2019\u201320 Gonzaga Bulldogs men's basketball team|Gonzaga]]\n|31\u20132\n|23rd\n|2019\n|}\n\n{{notelist}}\n\n==See also==\n* [[Impact of the 2019\u201320 coronavirus pandemic on sports]]\n* [[2020 NCAA Division I Women's Basketball Tournament]]\n* [[2020 NCAA Division II Men's Basketball Tournament]]\n* [[2020 NCAA Division III Men's Basketball Tournament]]\n* [[2020 NAIA Division I Men's Basketball Tournament]]\n* [[2020 National Invitation Tournament]]\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n{{NCAA Men's Division I Basketball Tournament navbox}}\n{{2020 NCAA Division I men's basketball tournament navbox}}\n{{2019\u201320 NCAA Division I championships navbox}}\n\n[[Category:2019\u201320 NCAA Division I men's basketball season|Ncaa Tournament]] \n[[Category:NCAA Division I Men's Basketball Tournament]]\n[[Category:Sports events cancelled due to the 2019\u201320 coronavirus pandemic|NCAA Division I Men's Basketball Tournament]]\n[[Category:Basketball in Georgia (U.S. state)]]\n[[Category:College sports in Georgia (U.S. state)]]\n[[Category:2020s in Atlanta]]\n", "text_old": "{{short description|United States top collegiate-level basketball tournament for 2020, cancelled due to COVID-19}}\n{{Infobox NCAA Basketball Tournament\n| Year=2020\t\n| Season= 2019\u201320\t\n| Image=2020 NCAA Men's Final Four logo.svg\n| Caption=\n| Teams=68\n| FinalFourArena=[[Mercedes-Benz Stadium]]\n| FinalFourCity=[[Atlanta]]\n| Champion=Coronavirus\n| TitleCount= \n| ChampGameCount = \n| ChampFFCount = \n| RunnerUp= \n| GameCount=\n| RunnerFFCount = \n| Semifinal1= \n| FinalFourCount= \n| Semifinal2= \n| FinalFourCount2= \n| Coach= \n| CoachCount=\n| MOP= \n| MOPTeam= \n| Attendance=\n| OneTopScorer= \n| TwoTopScorers=\n| TopScorer=\n| TopScorerTeam=\n| TopScorer2=\n| TopScorer2Team=\n| Points=\n}}\n\nThe '''2020 NCAA Division I Men's Basketball Tournament''' was a planned [[single-elimination tournament]] of 68 teams to determine the men's [[NCAA|National Collegiate Athletic Association]] (NCAA) [[NCAA Division I|Division I]] [[college basketball]] national champion for the [[2019\u201320 NCAA Division I men's basketball season|2019\u201320 season]]. On March 12, 2020, the tournament, as well as all other NCAA championships for the remainder of the academic season,  was cancelled in the wake of the [[2019\u201320 coronavirus pandemic|COVID-19 coronavirus pandemic]]. It was the first time [[NCAA Division I Men's Basketball Tournament|the tournament]] had been cancelled since its creation in [[1939 NCAA Men's Division I Basketball Tournament|1939]]. \n\n==2020 NCAA Tournament schedule and venues==\n{{Location map+|USA|width=450|float=right|caption=2020 First Four (orange) and first and second rounds (green)|places=\n{{Location map~|USA|mark=orange pog.svg|lat_deg=39.7404|lon_deg=-84.1792|position=left|background=#FFFFFF|label=Dayton|link=UD Arena}}\n{{Location map~|USA|mark=green pog.svg|lat_deg=27.950575|lon_deg=-82.457178|position=bottom|background=#FFFFFF|label=Tampa|link=Amalie Arena}}\n{{Location map~|USA|mark=green pog.svg|lat_deg=42.652579|lon_deg=-73.756232|position=left|background=#FFFFFF|label=Albany|link=Times Union Center}}\n{{Location map~|USA|mark=green pog.svg|lat_deg=47.666222|lon_deg=-117.422778|position=left|background=#FFFFFF|label=Spokane|link=Spokane Veterans Memorial Arena}}\n{{Location map~|USA|mark=green pog.svg|lat_deg=38.626667|lon_deg=-90.2025|position=bottom|background=#FFFFFF|label=St. Louis|link=Enterprise Center}}\n{{Location map~|USA|mark=green pog.svg|lat_deg=38.5556|lon_deg=-121.4689|position=bottom|background=#FFFFFF|label=Sacramento|link=Golden 1 Center}}\n{{Location map~|USA|mark=green pog.svg|lat_deg=41.496389|lon_deg=-81.688056|position=right|background=#FFFFFF|label=Cleveland|link=Rocket Mortgage FieldHouse}}\n{{Location map~|USA|mark=green pog.svg|lat_deg=36.059722|lon_deg=-79.825556|position=right|background=#FFFFFF|label=Greensboro|link=Greensboro Coliseum}}\n{{Location map~|USA|mark=green pog.svg|lat_deg=41.262667|lon_deg=-95.928206|position=left|background=#FFFFFF|label=Omaha|link=CHI Health Center Omaha}}\n}}\n\n{{Location map+|USA|width=450|float=right|caption=2020 Regionals (blue) and Final Four (red)|places=\n{{Location map~|USA|mark=blue pog.svg|lat_deg=39.7667|lon_deg=-86.15|position=left|background=#FFFFFF|label=Indianapolis|link=Lucas Oil Stadium}}\n{{Location map~|USA|mark=blue pog.svg|lat_deg=34.043056|lon_deg=-118.267222|position=bottom|background=#FFFFFF|label=Los Angeles|link=Staples Center}}\n{{Location map~|USA|mark=blue pog.svg|lat_deg=40.750556|lon_deg=-73.993611|position=bottom|background=#FFFFFF|label=New York City|link=Madison Square Garden}}\n{{Location map~|USA|mark=blue pog.svg|lat_deg=29.684722|lon_deg=-95.410833|position=top|background=#FFFFFF|label=Houston|link=Toyota Center}}\n{{Location map~|USA|mark=red pog.svg|lat_deg=33.748995|lon_deg=-84.387982|position=left|background=#FFFFFF|label=Atlanta|link=Mercedes-Benz Stadium}}\n}}\n\nThe following list contains the sites that were to host each round of the 2020 tournament:<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.ncaa.org/championships/future-division-i-mens-basketball-championship-sites|date=21 April 2017|publisher=[[NCAA]]|title=Future Division I Men's Basketball Championship sites}}</ref>\n\n'''First Four'''\n*March 17 and 18\n**[[UD Arena|University of Dayton Arena]], [[Dayton, Ohio]] (Host: [[University of Dayton]])\n\n'''First and Second Rounds'''\n*March 19 and 21\n** [[Times Union Center]], [[Albany, New York]] (Host: [[Metro Atlantic Athletic Conference]]/[[Siena College]])<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.siena.edu/news/story/siena-to-host-ncaa-basketball-tournament-next-three-years/|date=21 April 2017|publisher=[[Siena College]]|title=Siena to Host NCAA Basketball Tournament Next Three Years}}</ref>\n** [[Spokane Arena]], [[Spokane, Washington]] (Host: [[University of Idaho]])\n** [[Enterprise Center]], [[St. Louis|St. Louis, Missouri]] (Host: [[Missouri Valley Conference]])\n** [[Amalie Arena]], [[Tampa, Florida]] (Host: [[University of South Florida]])\n\n*March 20 and 22\n** [[Greensboro Coliseum Complex]], [[Greensboro, North Carolina]] (Host: [[Atlantic Coast Conference]])\n** [[CHI Health Center Omaha]], [[Omaha, Nebraska]] (Host: [[Creighton University]])\n** [[Golden 1 Center]], [[Sacramento, California]] (Host: [[Sacramento State University]])\n** [[Rocket Mortgage FieldHouse]], [[Cleveland|Cleveland, Ohio]] (Host: [[Mid-American Conference]]/[[Cleveland State University]])\n\n'''Regional Semifinals and Finals''' (Sweet Sixteen and Elite Eight)\n*March 26 and 28\n**'''Midwest Regional''', [[Lucas Oil Stadium]], [[Indianapolis|Indianapolis, Indiana]] (Host: [[Horizon League]]/[[Indiana University \u2013 Purdue University Indianapolis|IUPUI]])\n**'''West Regional''', [[Staples Center]], [[Los Angeles|Los Angeles, California]] (Host: [[Pepperdine University]])\n\n*March 27 and 29\n**'''South Regional''', [[Toyota Center]], [[Houston|Houston, Texas]] (Host: [[University of Houston]])\n**'''East Regional''', [[Madison Square Garden]], [[New York City|New York, New York]] (Host: [[St. John's University (New York City)|St. John's University]]/[[Big East Conference]])\n\n'''National Semifinals and Championship''' (Final Four and Championship)\n*April 4 and 6\n**[[Mercedes-Benz Stadium]], [[Atlanta|Atlanta, Georgia]] (Host: [[Georgia Tech|Georgia Institute of Technology]])\n\n==Coronavirus impact and cancellation ==\n{{See also|Impact of the 2019\u201320 coronavirus pandemic on sports}}\nThe timing of the tournament coincided with the wider spread of the [[Coronavirus disease 2019]] (COVID-19) [[2019\u201320 coronavirus pandemic|outbreak]] in the United States. On March 10, 2020, the [[Ivy League]] announced it had cancelled the conference's [[2020 Ivy League Men's Basketball Tournament|tournament]], and would award its championship and automatic qualification to [[2019\u201320 Yale Bulldogs men's basketball team|Yale]] based on regular season records. [[Harvard University]] was scheduled to host the event at [[Lavietes Pavilion]] in [[Boston]] on March 14 and 15.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.espn.com/mens-college-basketball/story/_/id/28877858/ivy-league-cancels-conference-basketball-tournaments-coronavirus|title=Ivy cancels conference tourneys, cites coronavirus|date=2020-03-10|website=ESPN.com|language=en|access-date=2020-03-27}}</ref> Some conferences subsequently announced they would go on with their tournaments while holding their games [[Behind closed doors (sport)|behind closed doors]] with no outside spectators and limited attendance, especially on March 11 (when the [[World Health Organization]] declared COVID-19 a [[pandemic]]).<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.usatoday.com/story/sports/ncaab/2020/03/11/ncaa-tournament-fans-banned-due-to-coronavirus-concerns/5024027002/|title=NCAA men's and women's basketball tournaments will not include fans due to coronavirus concerns|last=Schad|first=Tom|date=March 11, 2020|website=[[USA Today]]|access-date=March 11, 2020}}</ref>\n\nThe NCAA subsequently announced it would go on with its winter-sport championships, including its basketball tournaments, with attendance limited to essential staff and family members. Some venues (such as those in [[Ohio]] and [[California]]) enacted further local numerical restrictions on the numbers of those who could attend an event, which the NCAA agreed to respect.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.usatoday.com/story/sports/ncaab/2020/03/11/ncaa-tournament-fans-banned-due-to-coronavirus-concerns/5024027002/|title=NCAA men's and women's basketball tournaments will not include fans due to coronavirus concerns|author=Tom Schad|date=2020-03-11|publisher=USA Today|access-date=2020-03-11}}</ref> Reports also stated that for practicality reasons, the NCAA was considering re-locating some of the later rounds (including the regional finals and the Final Four, the latter scheduled to be held at the 71,000-seat Mercedes-Benz Stadium) to smaller venues within the same host cities.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://nypost.com/2020/03/11/march-madness-2020-could-change-final-four-venue-amid-coronavirus-crisis/|title=March Madness 2020 could change Final Four venue amid coronavirus crisis|last=Terranova|first=Justin|date=2020-03-11|website=New York Post|language=en|access-date=2020-03-12}}</ref> \n\nOn March 12, 2020, after the [[NBA]] [[Suspension of the 2019\u201320 NBA season|suspended its regular season]] following the diagnosis of a player with COVID-19,<ref name=\":0\">{{Cite news|url=https://www.wsj.com/articles/ncaa-medical-chief-says-testing-shortage-threatens-march-madness-11584030721|title=The Day Sports Shut Down|date=2020-03-12|work=Wall Street Journal|access-date=2020-03-28|url-status=live|language=en-US|issn=0099-9660}}</ref> all conferences that had not yet concluded tournament play announced they would be scrapping their tournaments. With the decision to cancel the [[2020 MEAC Men's Basketball Tournament|2020 Mid-Eastern Athletic Conference Tournament]], all games that had yet to be played in the basketball season were cancelled, while the [[Big East Conference|Big East]] called off its tournament at halftime during a quarter-final game between [[2019\u201320 Creighton Bluejays men's basketball team|Creighton]] and [[2019\u201320 St. John's Red Storm men's basketball team|St. John's]]. Most major conferences also announced suspensions of all athletics to varying degrees.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.espn.com/mens-college-basketball/story/_/id/28891602/big-ten-sec-american-cancel-conference-tournaments|title=Conference championships canceled across board|date=2020-03-12|website=ESPN.com|language=en|access-date=2020-03-28}}</ref><ref name=\":0\" /> Later in the day, the NCAA announced the tournament would be cancelled, along with all remaining winter and spring championships for the academic year.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.ncaa.org/about/resources/media-center/news/ncaa-cancels-remaining-winter-and-spring-championships|title=NCAA cancels remaining winter and spring championships|last=|first=|date=2020-03-12|website=NCAA.org|language=en|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=2020-03-28}}</ref>\n\nThe NCAA had not ruled out publishing what would have been its at-large selections and bracket.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.cbssports.com/college-basketball/news/ncaa-weighing-release-of-68-team-bracket-despite-cancellation-of-2020-ncaa-tournament-over-coronavirus/|title=NCAA weighing release of 68-team bracket despite cancellation of 2020 NCAA Tournament over coronavirus|website=CBSSports.com|language=en|access-date=2020-03-13}}</ref> Vice president of men's basketball Dan Gavitt told the [[Associated Press]] that he had proposed holding a shortened, 16-team tournament in Atlanta (split between [[State Farm Arena]] and Mercedes-Benz Stadium) as an alternative, with all participants chosen by the selection committee, before the decision was made to cancel the entire tournament due to [[Rudy Gobert]]'s diagnosis.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://apnews.com/e8f45446377951f539c6be58294ec0f6|title=AP Exclusive: NCAA tried to save March Madness with 16 teams|date=2020-03-13|agency=Associated Press|access-date=2020-03-13}}</ref> The NCAA ultimately decided against releasing any brackets, with Gavitt stating, \"Brackets based on hypotheticals can\u2019t substitute for a complete selection, seeding and bracketing process.\"<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.ncaa.com/news/basketball-men/article/2020-03-15/ncaas-gavitt-basketball-championship-brackets-will-not-be|title=NCAA\u2019s Gavitt: Basketball championship brackets will not be released for 2020 {{!}} NCAA.com|website=www.ncaa.com|language=en|access-date=2020-03-21}}</ref>\n\nAs part of a cycle that began in 2016, [[TBS (American TV channel)|TBS]] was scheduled to televise the 2020 Final Four and national championship game.<ref>{{cite web |title=CBS Sports and Turner Sports announce 2020 March Madness commentators |url=https://www.ncaa.com/news/basketball-men/article/2020-03-10/cbs-sports-and-turner-sports-announce-2020-ncaa-division-i |publisher=NCAA |accessdate=10 March 2020 |date=10 March 2020 |df=mdy-all}}</ref> [[CBS]] was scheduled to televise the selection show.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.usatoday.com/story/sports/ncaab/2020/03/03/ncaa-tournament-selection-sunday-show-cbs-reveal-brackets-first/4942393002/|title=CBS will stick with popular brackets-first format for NCAA tournament Selection Sunday show|last=Gleeson|first=Scott|website=USA Today|language=en-US|access-date=2020-03-05}}</ref> [[CBS Sports]] and [[Turner Sports]] announced on March 16 that all technicians and utility staff who were expected to work the ''[[NCAA March Madness (TV program)|NCAA March Madness]]'' coverage would still be paid.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.sportsvideo.org/2020/03/16/cbs-sports-will-pay-all-march-madness-technicians-and-utilities-including-freelancers/|title=CBS Sports, Turner Sports Will Pay All March Madness Technicians and Utilities, Including Freelancers|last=Digital|first=Brandon Costa, Director of|website=Sports Video Group|language=en|access-date=2020-03-17}}</ref> Radio rightsholder [[Westwood One]] announced plans to offer encores of radio broadcasts from classic NCAA tournament games\u2014accompanied by interviews with notable figures from the respective games\u2014to fill the time slots it had originally devoted to the tournament.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://awfulannouncing.com/ncaa/westwood-one-will-air-classic-ncaa-tournament-games-in-its-normal-tournament-windows.html|title=Westwood One will air classic NCAA Tournament games in its normal tournament windows|date=2020-03-18|website=Awful Announcing|language=en-US|access-date=2020-03-18}}</ref> CBS similarly announced on March 19 that it would also air nine classic Final Four games across the weekend afternoons of March 21, 22, and 29.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://nypost.com/2020/03/20/cbs-giving-fans-march-madness-fix-of-classic-games/|title=CBS giving fans March Madness fix of classic games|last=Joyce|first=Greg|date=2020-03-20|website=New York Post|language=en|access-date=2020-03-20}}</ref>\n==Automatic qualifiers==\nThe following teams had automatically qualified for the 2020 NCAA field by virtue of winning their conference's tournament. All conference tournaments that had not been completed were cancelled, the majority of which without naming an automatic qualifier.\n<!-- DO NOT add any additional automatic bids without a reliable source saying they were an automatic bid. -->\n{|class=\"wikitable sortable plainrowheaders\" style=\"text-align:center;\"\n!scope=\"col\"|Conference\n!scope=\"col\"|Team\n!scope=\"col\" data-sort-type=\"number\"|Record\n!scope=\"col\" data-sort-type=\"number\"|Appearance\n!scope=\"col\"|Last bid\n|-\n|align=left|[[2020 America East Men's Basketball Tournament|America East]]\n!scope=\"row\" style=\"text-align:left\"|[[2019\u201320 Vermont Catamounts men's basketball team|Vermont]] {{efn|name=Vermont|Vermont received the automatic bid<ref>{{cite web|url=\nhttps://www.burlingtonfreepress.com/story/sports/college/vermont/2020/03/12/america-east-basketball-restricted-attendance-title-game-uvm-amid-covid-19-concerns/5030220002/ |title=America East championship, NCAA Tournament canceled amid COVID\u201019 concerns |accessdate=March 12, 2020}}</ref> after the America East Tournament was cancelled due to the [[2020 coronavirus pandemic in the United States|Coronavirus pandemic]].}}\n|26-7\n|8th\n|2019\n|-\n|align=left|[[2020 American Athletic Conference Men's Basketball Tournament|American]]\n! colspan=\"4\"| Tournament cancelled, no automatic bid\n|-\n|align=left|[[2020 Atlantic 10 Men's Basketball Tournament|Atlantic 10]]\n! colspan=\"4\"| Tournament cancelled, no automatic bid\n|-\n|align=left|[[2020 ACC Men's Basketball Tournament|ACC]]\n!scope=\"row\" style=\"text-align:left\"|[[2019\u201320 Florida State Seminoles men's basketball team|Florida State]] {{efn|name=Florida State|Florida State received the automatic bid<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.cbssports.com/college-basketball/news/2020-acc-tournament-canceled-amid-coronavirus-pandemic-concerns/live/ |title=2020 ACC Tournament canceled amid coronavirus pandemic concerns |last=Boone |first=Kyle |date=March 12, 2020 |website=CBSSports.com|publisher=CBS Sports |access-date=March 13, 2020}}</ref> after the ACC Tournament was cancelled due to the [[2020 coronavirus pandemic in the United States|Coronavirus pandemic]].}}\n|26\u20135\n|18th\n|2019\n|-\n|align=left|[[2020 Atlantic Sun Men's Basketball Tournament|Atlantic Sun]]\n!scope=\"row\" style=\"text-align:left\"|[[2019\u201320 Liberty Flames basketball team|Liberty]]\n|30\u20134\n|5th\n|2019\n|-\n|align=left|[[2020 Big 12 Men's Basketball Tournament|Big 12]]\n! colspan=\"4\"| Tournament cancelled, no automatic bid\n|-\n|align=left|[[2020 Big East Men's Basketball Tournament|Big East]]\n! colspan=\"4\"| Tournament cancelled, no automatic bid\n|-\n|align=left|[[2020 Big Sky Conference Men's Basketball Tournament|Big Sky]]\n! colspan=\"4\"| Tournament cancelled, no automatic bid\n|-\n|align=left|[[2020 Big South Conference Men's Basketball Tournament|Big South]]\n!scope=\"row\" style=\"text-align:left\"|[[2019\u201320 Winthrop Eagles men's basketball team|Winthrop]]\n|24\u201310\n|11th\n|2017\n|-\n|align=left|[[2020 Big Ten Conference Men's Basketball Tournament|Big Ten]]\n! colspan=\